Europe
------
[1] HPA update (Europe)
Date: 28 Oct 2011
Source: Health Protection Report, Volume 5 No 43. [abridged & edited]
http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/archives/2011/news4711.htm#msls


The 5th European monthly measles monitoring (EMMO) surveillance report
has been published by the European Centre for Disease Prevention and
Prevention (ECDC) [European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control
(ECDC). European measles monthly monitoring, October 2011. Stockholm:
ECDC; 2011. Available from:
http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/Forms/ECDC_DispForm.aspx?ID=778].


Although no new outbreaks were reported in the 29 EU and EEA/EFTA
countries during October 2011, over 1000 new measles cases were
detected through epidemic intelligence, bringing the total number of
cases for 2011 to more than 30 200. Two cases of sub-acute sclerosing
panencephalitis [see moderator's comment at end], one of whom died,
were reported in October 2011. Between January and September 2011, 8
measles-related deaths and 23 cases of acute measles encephalitis were
reported.

The Regional Office for Europe published its Epidemiological Brief in
October 2011 covering the measles outbreaks and preventative measures
taken across 53 member countries [World Health Organisation, Regional
Office for Europe (WHO Europe). WHO Epidemiological Brief: a monthly
publication on vaccine-preventable diseases and immunisation data and
analysis, No. 18 (October 2011). Available from:
http://www.euro.who.int/__data/assets/pdf_file/0006/153195/Epi_Brief_Issue_18.pdf].
This report highlights the nearly 3-fold increase in cases compared to
the same period in 2007. The wider impact of the outbreaks in Europe
was also examined and, in particular, the link between the resurgence
in measles in South America and its connection with Europe.

956 Confirmed measles cases in England and Wales up to the end of
October 2011
------------
In England and Wales, 956 laboratory confirmed measles cases have been
reported to the end of October 2011. Following the peak in April 2011,
the monthly total of confirmed cases has been falling with between 53
and 68 confirmed cases reported in the last 3 months. The majority of
cases are in unvaccinated individuals (92 percent total).

Outbreaks in schools and small family clusters are continuing to
occur, particularly in London (401 cases) and the South East (255
cases) regions, where most cases have been diagnosed. A history of
travel abroad or contact with someone who had travelled was the source
for infection for 150 confirmed cases this year [2011].

