******
[2] Ireland (East)
Date: Thu 24 Nov 2011
Source: Epi-Insight, Volume 12, Issue 11, November 2011 [abridged &
edited]
http://ndsc.newsweaver.ie/epiinsight/1fng5qmgsrbbsjyxp8wi4b?a=1&p=18519345&t=17517774


Measles is highly infectious and can cause severe illness and
occasionally death. Following exposure, up to 90 percent of
susceptible people develop measles. The virus can be transmitted from
4 days before the rash becomes visible to 4 days after the rash
appears.

Measles cases in this outbreak were 1st notified in HSE-East [Health
Service Executive-East] in early February 2011. There was a gradual
increase in notifications through the summer months. However, from
early August 2011 (week 31), there was a marked increase in the weekly
notification of cases, to a maximum of 23 cases notified in one week
in late August 2011. By the end of week 42, 265 cases had been
reported nationally; 227 (86 percent) were from HSE-E.

The majority of these cases, 139 (61 percent) were reported during
August and September 2011 (weeks 32-41) from the north city areas of
Community Care Areas 6, 7 and 8 (Dublin northwest, Dublin north
central and Dublin north, respectively). This large increase in cases
was primarily due to a cluster of measles in school age children in a
residential summer camp in north Dublin, which subsequently spread in
the north inner city and Ballymun areas.

During this outbreak period (weeks 32-41), all age groups were
affected. However, the 5-9 year old had the greatest number of cases.
Almost 70 percent of cases were unvaccinated or incompletely
vaccinated. During this time, there were 11 hospitalisations, and the
most frequent reported reason was for the treatment of seizures (3
cases).

Control measures
--------------
An outbreak control team chaired by the Director of Public Health
(HSE-E) with representatives from public health, community medicine,
the Health Protection Surveillance Centre (HPSC), and the National
Immunisation Office (NIO) was established. Among the outbreak measures
were the following:

- A schools' based "Blitz of MMR" in north inner city Dublin and
Ballymun took place in early September 2011 of all children attending
primary school who had not received the recommended MMR vaccination.
- Prompt follow-up of all reported measles cases by public health
staff including liaising with general practitioners, managing clusters
of measles, arranging swabs for diagnosis, staffing vaccination
clinics and advising cases on appropriate follow-up.
- Informing all Dublin GPs by letter and email of the measles
outbreak and requesting to opportunistically vaccinate all children
with MMR.
- Informing GPs in the outbreak area of additional outbreak measures,
including the vaccination of infants from 6 months and the expediting
of MMR2 in specific circumstances.
- Providing information on the outbreak to acute hospital services,
pharmacists and the Department of Education.
- Releasing multiple media messages to the public through the print
media and local and national radio informing the public of the
outbreak and of the need to have MMR vaccination to protect against
measles.

Since early October [2011], there has been a gradual decline in the
number of measles cases reported weekly in HSE-E to 3 cases reported
in the week ending 2 Oct 2011. A combination of factors is likely to
have facilitated the spread of measles in the affected area including:
suboptimal MMR uptake, social deprivation, high population density,
and the absence of a school based immunisation service.

Vaccination with MMR is the only way to prevent measles infection.
However, nationally and in HSE-E, the MMR vaccination uptake at 24
months is currently 90 percent, which is too low to prevent measles
outbreaks from occurring. MMR vaccine is safe and highly effective in
preventing measles and its complications. Achieving a high
immunisation rate with MMR vaccine is the only way to prevent
measles.

