Africa
------
[3] Kenya (Mwingi)
Date: Sat 26 Nov 2011
Source: The Star [edited]
http://www.the-star.co.ke/local/northeastern/50993-14-kavonokya-sect-members-with-measles-hospitalised


Eleven critically ill children and 3 women of the Kavonokya
[religious] sect have been forcefully admitted at Mwingi District
Hospital following a outbreak of measles. The sick were rounded up
during an operation by Mwingi public health personnel led by the
district head David Munyoki. By Wednesday [23 Nov 2011], 501 sect
members' children had been immunised against measles. The
immunisation, backed by armed police officers, was launched after 11
children died from measles in Ngoo sub-location of Mwingi East
district in the past 2 months.

Kavonokya members do not take their children to hospital because they
claim it is against their faith. A Star [journalist] visited the
patients admitted to an isolated ward at the hospital. Munyoki said
the children and their mothers are responding well to treatment. He
said the patients were isolated to avoid cross-infection of other
patients in the hospital. "The rest of the people have received
immunisation, and only members of the Kavonokya sect do not take their
own for immunization. We could not put them together with other
patients," pointed out the public health officer.

Munyoki said 14 villages in Lundi and Ngoo areas of Mwingi East have
been covered in the immunisation programme. He added that the
immunization will be held monthly to ensure all targeted sect members
are inoculated. "We have not faced any serious resistance during our
operation due to the cooperation we are getting from the provincial
administration, who have provided use of police officers to enforce
the programme," said Munyoki.

He added that not only were the Kavonokya children being forcefully
immunized, but plans were underway to arrest and charge them in court
for violating children rights to access health care. The immunization
and the forceful treatment for members of the Kavonokya sect came days
after the Health authorities in Eastern Province proposed the
proscribing of the sect for putting the health of their adherents at
risk.

The provincial public health officer Carol Ndegwa made the demand in
Mwingi when she was the chief guest during the world toilets day
celebrations at Yongooni village in Nuu division of Mwingi East on
Saturday [26 Nov 2011]. She said 11 children died of measles after
their Kavonokya sect parents failed to take them for medication or
immunization, as it was allegedly against their faith.

She said it was the constitutional right of all Kenyans to have good
health and access to medical care. She warned that people who violate
the constitution by denying children access to health care on account
of religion would be arrested and prosecuted.

In early September [2011], police officers raided the home of a
Kavonokya sect adherent in Mwingi East district and rescued 3 sickly
children whom they forcefully took to hospital. A contingent of police
officers led by Mwingi OCS Jonathan Wafula was summoned to the home of
Mbevo Musili in Kyamwenze village in Mui division by the assistant
chief Julius Musyoka Mukiti after the brother of the sick children had
passed away as a result of measles infection on the previous day. The
Ngoo assistant chief had summoned the police after he earlier stormed
the home and stopped the burial of the Mui Secondary school student,
insisting that he would only issue a burial permit after the
deceased's 3 other sick siblings were taken for medical attention.

[Byline: Misembi Nzengu]

