[6] Australia (ACT)
Date: Wed 23 Nov 2011
Source: The Canberra Times [edited]
http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/health/measles-outbreak-at-orana-school/2368500.aspx


A student from the Orana Steiner School has been admitted to hospital
with measles, and at least 3 of his classmates have been diagnosed
with the illness. ACT [Australian Capital Territory] Chief Health
Officer Paul Kelly has written to parents at the school today [23 Nov
2011], saying: "We are asking parents of students at Orana School to
be alert to measles symptoms. The Health Protection Service has begun
contacting people believed to have been exposed, recommending post
exposure prophylaxis in line with national guidelines. Priority has
been given to contacting the households and those most recently
exposed contacts at GP surgeries and the Canberra Hospital. The
guidelines require the measles mumps and rubella vaccine to be given
within 3 days or normal human immunoglobulin within 6 days." Parents
of any unvaccinated students in the same class as the students with
measles are being asked to exclude their child from school until the
end of next week.

Symptoms of measles include fever, tiredness, runny nose, and a cough,
followed by a rash which appears 2-7 days later. People generally
develop symptoms 7-18 days after being exposed to a person with
infectious measles. Ten days is considered normal. About one in every
1000 people with measles develops encephalitis.

Orana deputy director Marie-Anne Gigon said the school was working
closely with the Health Directorate to halt the spread of measles
through the school.

[Byline: Peter Jean, Jacqueline Williams]

